Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Given the time lag between dates of onset of paralysis and final laboratory testing of virus isolates, cases with dates of onset in 2018 are still being confirmed. That being said, 2018 continues to have cases confirmed -- both cVDPV and WPV -- bringing the annual totals of confirmed cases above that seen in 2017.

While there were no official reports of WPV1-associated disease in this week's update, the media report below mentions the confirmation of a polio-associated AFP (acute flaccid paralysis) case in Lakki Marwat district, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province. Presumably this case will be officially reported in the coming weeks. But there have been positive WPV1 isolates from environmental samples taken in December 2018 in both Afghanistan and Pakistan, confirming that the virus is still circulating in both countries.

The disturbing piece of news is the confirmation of a cVDPV2-associated polio case in Mozambique. Unfortunately, reading between the lines, it is possible that the mOPV2 (monovalent oral poliovaccine type 2) campaign held in Mozambique in 2017 is related to the cVDPV2 identified last year [2018]. If so, this may be the 2nd incident of cVDPV2-associated polio following mOPV2 campaigns (see Poliomyelitis update (02): DR Congo, cVDPV, WHO, China, vaccine challenges 20190109.6250155 for details on the 1st case in DR Congo). Concerns regarding a vicious circle of cVDPV-associated polio cases, immunization campaigns with mOPV2, followed by 1-2 years with additional cVDPV2 cases . . . a very difficult conundrum. Is the time approaching to leave OPV? We now have 29 cases of WPV-associated disease (the wild poliovirus) and 101 cases of cVDPV-associated disease in 2018.

For a map showing the locations of cases of WPV and cVDPV, see http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/.

HealthMap/ProMED-mail maps of the countries discussed in the update above:
